\section{Open Problems} 
\label{sec:open_problems}

In this section we discuss how the results of this paper can be furthered.
This paper has two threads: relating skew-symmetric D-optimal designs to certain tournaments and characterising large principal submatrices of conference matrices by their spectra.

Armario~\cite{Armario15} showed that the existence of skew-symmetric EW matrices is equivalent to the existence of certain tournaments that he called \textbf{EW tournaments}.
By Theorem~\ref{thm:Aconj}, we have that EW tournaments are determined by their spectrum.

We can consider the analogous question for symmetric EW matrices.

\begin{problem}
	What combinatorial structures are related to symmetric EW matrices?
\end{problem}

By definition, a skew-symmetric D-optimal design has constant diagonal $1$.
The symmetric case is not constrained in this way.
It is, however, natural to begin by asking whether symmetric EW matrices can have constant diagonals.
We show that symmetric EW matrices cannot have constant diagonals.

\begin{proposition}\label{pro:noGraphical}
	Let $M$ be a symmetric EW matrix.
	Then $M$ does not have a constant diagonal.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
	Suppose that $M$ has a constant diagonal and order $4t+2$ for some $t$.
	Then we can write either $M = J - 2A$ or $M  = J - 2A - 2I$ where $A$ is the adjacency matrix of some graph $\Gamma$.
	In either case, modulo $4$ we have $M^2 \equiv 2J + 2(AJ + JA)$.
	On the other hand, since $M$ is an EW matrix we have $M^2 \equiv 
	\left ( \begin{smallmatrix}
		2J & O \\ O & 2J
	\end{smallmatrix} \right )$.
	Now, the $(i,j)$-th entry of the matrix $AJ + JA$ is given by $d_i + d_j$ where $d_i$ is equal to the degree of the $i$th vertex of $\Gamma$.
	By above we see that vertices of $\Gamma$ are partitioned into two parts of size $2t+1$ with the vertices of one part having even degree and the vertices of the other part having odd degree.
	Summing the degrees of every vertex of a graph counts each edge twice and hence the sum must be even.
	But the sum of the degrees of the vertices of $\Gamma$ is odd.
	Hence we have a contradiction, as required.
\end{proof}

A $\{ \pm 1 \}$-matrix of order $n$ is called a \textbf{Barba matrix} if $B B^\top = (n-1)I+J$.
Symmetric EW matrices can be constructed from symmetric Barba matrices.
Indeed, let $B$ be a symmetric Barba matrix of order $n$ and let $H_2$ be a Hadamard matrix of order $2$. 
Then the tensor product of $B$ and $H_2$ is a symmetric EW-matrix of order $2n$. 

The second thread of this paper was about showing that conference matrices of order $n$ can be reconstructed from principal submatrices of order $n-3$.
Using Lemma~\ref{lem:switchingForm} and its proof, we see that the existence of skew-symmetric EW matrices of order $4t+2$ is equivalent to the existence of Seidel matrices $S$ with characteristic polynomial $\chi_S(x) = (x^2 + 8t+1)(x^2+4t-1)^{2t}$.
Furthermore, $S+I$ is equivalent to a skew-symmetric EW matrix.
Therefore we can think of $S$ as the analogue of skew-symmetric conference matrices.

\begin{proposition}\label{pro:EWconf}
	Let $S$ be a Seidel matrix with characteristic polynomial $\chi_S(x) = (x^2 + 8t+1)(x^2+4t-1)^{2t}$.
	Then there exists a Seidel matrix with characteristic polynomial $\chi_S(x) = x(x^2 + 8t-1)(x^2+4t-1)^{2t-1}$.
\end{proposition}
\begin{proof}
	Follows using Theorem~\ref{thm:interlacing}, Proposition~\ref{pro:basic}, and Proposition~\ref{pro:skewProps}.
\end{proof}

Using our methods from Section~\ref{sec:submatrices_of_skew_hadamard_matrices}, we were unable to prove the converse of this proposition.

\begin{problem}
	Is the converse of Proposition~\ref{pro:EWconf} true?
\end{problem}


















